    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "EP",
    "text": "The piece that I will be playing tonight is called 'Agony Crematorium,' written by one of this composers, Eliezar Ben Israel, that perished in his way during the Holocaust periods to the concentration camp. [SIGHS] [MUSIC - 'AGONY CREMATORIUM'] I would like to introduce now the other violinist. That this happened to be my wife, Barbara Fish Polidi that is artist soloist in her own right, teacher of violin. We'll be performing now one Rhapsody that have very special place in this collection of lost voices, because is describing the triumph of the Jewish spirit over the dark forces of the violence, over the dark forces of the darkness, over the dark forces of the war. This piece also is transcribed for violin solo and orchestra, violin solo and piano. Now, we have one of the versions of this for two violins alone. Thank you. [MUSIC - 'RHAPSODY'] This was the good-- good old days of my parents. The year is approximately 1937. Perhaps they're walking throughout some of these reunions, with social unions with their friends. My father is carrying some kind of present there. And this is nice summery day in Sofia Bulgaria.",
